# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2-butoxyethanol
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Miscibility of 2-butoxyethanol with water depends on temperature.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Depending on the composition of the mixture, the two liquids are partially miscible.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] This mixture shows both a lower and an upper critical solution temperature: below around 49 °C (lower critical solution temperature), the liquids are completely miscible.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] The same is true for temperatures above around 130 °C (upper critical solution temperature).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Between these temperatures, however, the liquids do not mix in all proportions and two phases might appear, each of which is formed by various ratios of the two liquids.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] or the etherification of butanol with 2-chloroethanol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol can be obtained in the laboratory by performing a ring opening of 2-propyl-1,3-dioxolane with boron trichloride.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] It is often produced industrially by combining ethylene glycol and butyraldehyde in a Parr reactor with palladium on carbon.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] In 2006, the European production of butyl glycol ethers amounted to 181 kilotons, of which approximately 50% (90 kt/a) was 2-butoxyethanol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] World production is estimated to be 200 to 500 kt/a, of which 75% is for paints and coatings and 18% for metal cleaners and household cleaners.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] In the US, it is considered a high production volume chemical because more than 100 million pounds of this chemical are produced per year.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol is a glycol ether with modest surfactant properties, which can also be used as a mutual solvent (soluble in both water and oil).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol is a solvent for paints and surface coatings, as well as cleaning products and inks.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Products containing this compound are commonly found at construction sites, automobile repair shops, print shops, and facilities that produce sterilizing and cleaning products.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] It is the main ingredient of many home, commercial and industrial cleaning solutions.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Since the molecule has both polar and non-polar ends, 2-butoxyethanol is useful for removing both polar and non-polar substances, like grease and oils.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] FDA to be used as direct and indirect food additives, which include antimicrobial agents, defoamers, stabilizers, and adhesives.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol is commonly produced for the oil industry because of its surfactant properties.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] In the petroleum industry, 2-butoxyethanol is a component of fracturing fluids, drilling stabilizers, and oil slick dispersants for both water-based and oil-based hydraulic fracturing.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] When liquid is pumped into the well, the fracturing fluids are pumped under extreme pressure, so 2-butoxyethanol is used to stabilize them by lowering the surface tension.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] As a surfactant, 2-butoxyethanol absorbs at the oil-water interface of the fracture.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] The compound is also used to facilitate the release of the gas by preventing congealing.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] It is also used as a crude oil–water coupling solvent for more general oil well workovers.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Because of its surfactant properties, it is a major constituent (30–60% w/w) in the oil spill dispersant Corexit 9527, which was widely used in the aftermath of the 2010 Deepwater Horizon oil spill.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol has a low acute toxicity, with LD50 of 2.5 g/kg in rats.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] National Toxicology Program have shown that only sustained exposure to high concentrations (100–500 ppm) of 2-butoxyethanol can cause adrenal tumors in animals.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists (ACGIH) reports that 2-butoxyethanol is carcinogenic in rodents.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] These rodent tests may not directly translate to carcinogenicity in humans, as the observed mechanism of cancer involves the rodents' forestomach, which humans lack.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] OSHA does not regulate 2-butoxyethanol as a carcinogen.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol has not been shown to penetrate shale rock in a study conducted by Manz.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol can be disposed of by incineration.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] It was shown that disposal occurs faster in the presence of semiconductor particles.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol usually decomposes in the presence of air within a few days by reacting with oxygen radicals.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] It has not been identified as a major environmental contaminant, nor is it known to bio-accumulate.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol biodegrades in soils and water, with a half life of 1–4 weeks in aquatic environments.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol most commonly enters the human body system through dermal absorption, inhalation, or oral consumption of the chemical.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] The ACGIH threshold limit value (TLV) for worker exposure is 20 ppm, which is well above the odor detection threshold of 0.4 ppm.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Blood or urine concentrations of 2-butoxyethanol or the metabolite 2-butoxyacetic acid may be measured using chromatographic techniques.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] A biological exposure index of 200 mg 2-butoxyacetic acid per g creatinine has been established in an end-of-shift urine specimen for U.S. employees.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol and its metabolites fall to undetectable levels in urine after about 30 hours in men.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Harmful effects have been observed in nonhuman mammals exposed to high levels of 2-butoxyethanol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Developmental effects were seen in a study that exposed pregnant Fischer 344 rats, a type of laboratory rat, and New Zealand white rabbits to varying doses of 2-butoxyethanol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] At 100 ppm (483 mg/m3) and 200 ppm (966 mg/m3) exposure, statistically significant increases were observed in the number of litters with skeletal defects.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Additionally, 2-butoxyethanol was associated with a significant decrease in maternal body weight, uterine weight, and number of total implants.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol is metabolized in mammals by the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Neurological effects have also been observed in animals exposed to 2-butoxyethanol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Fischer 344 rats exposed to 2-butoxyethanol at concentrations of 523 ppm and 867 ppm experienced decreased coordination.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Male rabbits showed a loss of coordination and equilibrium after exposure to 400 ppm of 2-butoxyethanol for two days.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] When exposed to 2-butoxyethanol in drinking water, both F344/N rats and B63F1 mice showed negative effects.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] The range of exposure for the two species was between 70 mg/kg body weight per day to 1300 mg/kg body weight per day.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Decreased body weight and water consumption were seen for both species.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Rats had reduced red blood cell counts and thymus weights, as well as lesions in the liver, spleen, and bone marrow.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Environment and Health Canada recommended that 2-butoxyethanol be added to Schedule 1 of the Canadian Environmental Protection Act, 1999 (CEPA).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Under these regulations, products containing 2-butoxyethanol are to be diluted below a certain concentration.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Only those in which the user performs the required dilution are required to include it on labelling information.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol is listed in California as a hazardous substance and the state sets an 8 hour average airborne concentration exposure limit at 25 ppm, and in California employers are required to inform employees when they are working with it.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] 2-Butoxyethanol is prohibited from use as a chemical additive in hydraulic fracturing fluids (Rule 437, Table 437-1) in Colorado where all chemicals used in downhole operations are required to be disclosed (§34-60-132 C.R.S.) to the Energy and Carbon Management Commission.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] After its deletion from a UN list of substances requiring special toxicity labeling in 1994, and a subsequent petition by the American Chemistry Council, 2-butoxyethanol was removed from the U.S.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] Environmental Protection Agency's list of hazardous air pollutants in 2004.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-butoxyethanol] The safety of products containing 2-butoxyethanol as normally used is defended by the industry trade groups the American Chemistry Council and the Soap and Detergent Association.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] This application has been supplanted by the more economic direct oxidation of ethylene.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] Otherwise chloroethanol is still used in the production of pharmaceuticals, biocides, and plasticizers.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] Many of these applications entail its use in installing 2-hydroxyethyl groups.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] Several dyes are prepared by the alkylation of aniline derivatives with chloroethanol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] It is also used for manufacture of thiodiglycol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] It is a solvent for cellulose acetate and ethyl cellulose, textile printing dyes, in dewaxing, refining of rosin, extraction of pine lignin, and the cleaning of machines.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] Chloroethanol is a metabolite in the degradation of 1,2-dichloroethane.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] The alcohol is then further oxidized via chloroacetaldehyde to chloroacetate.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] This metabolic pathway is topical since billions of kilograms of 1,2-dichloroethane are processed annually as a precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] 2-Chloroethanol is toxic with an LD50 of 89 mg/kg in rats.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] Like most organochlorine compounds, chloroethanol releases hydrochloric acid and phosgene when burned.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] It is classified as an extremely hazardous substance in the United States as defined in Section 302 of the U.S.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] Emergency Planning and Community Right-to-Know Act (42 U.S.C.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-chloroethanol] 11002), and is subject to strict reporting requirements by facilities which produce, store, or use it in significant quantities.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] 2-Ethoxyethanol is manufactured by the reaction of ethylene oxide with ethanol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] As with other glycol ethers, 2-ethoxyethanol has the useful property of being able to dissolve chemically diverse compounds.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] It will dissolve oils, resins, grease, waxes, nitrocellulose, and lacquers.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-ethoxyethanol] This is an ideal property as a multi-purpose cleaner, and, therefore, 2-ethoxyethanol is used in products such as varnish removers and degreasing solutions.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] 2-Methoxyethanol is used as a solvent for many different purposes such as varnishes, dyes, and resins.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] It is also used as an additive in airplane deicing solutions.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] In organometallic chemistry it is commonly used for the synthesis of Vaska's complex and related compounds such as carbonylchlorohydridotris(triphenylphosphine)ruthenium (II).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] During these reactions the alcohol acts as a source of hydride and carbon monoxide.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] 2-Methoxyethanol is toxic to the bone marrow and testicles.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] Workers exposed to high levels are at risk for granulocytopenia, macrocytic anemia, oligospermia, and azoospermia.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] The methoxyethanol is converted by alcohol dehydrogenase into methoxyacetic acid which is the substance which causes the harmful effects.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] Both ethanol and acetate have a protecting effect.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] The methoxyacetate can enter the Krebs cycle where it forms methoxycitrate.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] In 2024, a group led by researchers at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology reported the discovery of 2-methoxyethanol in a star-forming region within the nebula NGC 6334.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] The discovery was made by examining in the laboratory the spectral signature of 2-methoxyethanol as the molecule was made to rotate.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/2-methoxyethanol] This signature was then sought in observational data for the region collected by the Atacama Large Millimeter Array, and 25 of its spectral lines were detected, constituting a secure identification of the molecule in the astronomical data.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The **American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists** (**ACGIH**) is a professional association of industrial hygienists and practitioners of related professions, with headquarters in Cincinnati, Ohio.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] One of its goals is to advance worker protection by providing timely, objective, scientific information to occupational and environmental health professionals.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The National Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists (NCGIH) convened on June 27, 1938, in Washington, D.C.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] NCGIH's original constitution limited full membership to two representatives from each governmental industrial hygiene agency.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Associate membership was made available to other professional personnel of the agencies holding full memberships, and also to personnel of educational institutions engaged in teaching industrial hygiene.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Governmental industrial hygiene personnel of other countries were eligible for affiliated membership.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The Conference came into being with 59 members, one affiliated member, and 16 associate members.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Forty-three members, one associate and six guests, attended the initial Conference.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] All but five of the members were from health departments.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The New York and Massachusetts state labor departments each had two present, and one from the West Virginia state compensation commission.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] At the end of World War II, many individuals were leaving governmental employment and membership in the Conference declined from the peak of 281 in 1944 to 235 in 1946.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Changes due to the transition to a peacetime economy, the development of other professional associations, and changes in the technical and administrative needs of state and local agencies, required the Conference to revise its constitution and make some major changes in its organizational structure.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The 1946 constitution revisions abandoned the concept of limiting full membership to only two individuals from each governmental industrial hygiene agency.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] This opened the doors to all of their professional personnel to participate in the activities of the organization on an equal basis.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Governmental industrial hygiene personnel from foreign countries were also given the right to full membership.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] These changes, among others, were to have a salutary effect on the organization which, in 1946, changed its name to the American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists (ACGIH).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] In the mid-1950s, steady growth in membership resumed and by 1960 there were 511 members, including 54 from other countries.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] During the next decade these numbers more than doubled and in 1977 the total reached 1,800, of which 166 were from outside the United States.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] For over 75 years, ACGIH has been dedicated to the industrial hygiene and occupational and environmental health and safety communities.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] They have grown and expanded without losing sight of their original goal - to encourage the interchange of experience among industrial hygiene workers and to collect and make accessible such information and data as might be of aid to them in the proper fulfillment of their duties.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] This original goal is reflected in both their current mission - the advancement of occupational and environmental health - and in their tagline: Defining the Science of Occupational and Environmental Health.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] As of 2016, nine ACGIH committees focus their energies on a range of topics: agricultural safety and health, air sampling instruments, bioaerosols, biological exposure indices, industrial ventilation, international, small business, chemical substance TLVs, and physical agent TLVs.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The *Applied Occupational and Environmental Hygiene* journal, was published from 1990 through 2003 and was formerly published as *Applied Industrial Hygiene* from 1986 through 1989.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] This ACGIH peer-reviewed journal provided scientific information and data to members until ACGIH and AIHA began publishing a joint journal.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The *Journal of Occupational and Environmental Hygiene* (JOEH) is a joint publication of the American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA) and ACGIH.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] JOEH is a peer-reviewed journal devoted to enhancing the knowledge and practice of occupational and environmental hygiene and safety by widely disseminating research articles and applied studies of the highest quality.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The activities of each Committee are directed by an individual mission statement.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Mission - To promote those activities and programs necessary to our suited for agriculture or agro-business and to increase awareness of occupational health, safety, and environmental issues affecting this underserved population worldwide.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Mission - To report on the availability, efficiency, use, and limitations of existing and new sampling methodology and instrumentation.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Mission - To compile and disseminate information on biologically derived contaminants that may become airborne, to develop recommendations for assessment, control, remediation, and prevention of such hazards, and to establish criteria for bioaerosol exposure limits.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Mission - To develop occupational biological exposure guidelines that are scientifically valid and supported by professional judgment, up-to-date, well-documented, understandable, clear, and produced by a clearly defined process that is balanced and free of conflict of interest.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Mission - To provide a safe and healthful environment by integrating state-of-the-art information from government and industry sources, using them to develop and recommend ventilation and other engineering controls to capture, collect, filter, and remove airborne contaminants from the workplace.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Mission - To help develop and support ACGIH's international initiatives.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Mission - To develop and disseminate practical information that operators of small businesses and their employees can apply to the recognition, evaluation, and control of workplace hazards and to assist education safety and health professionals in working with small business concerns.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Mission - To recommend airborne concentrations of agents and exposure conditions for use in the practice of industrial hygiene and by other qualified professionals to protect worker health.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Mission - To develop and disseminate occupational exposure guidelines that are evidence-based, scientifically valid, and rigorously review.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] ACGIH establishes the Threshold Limit Values (TLVs) for chemical substances, physical agents, and Biological Exposure Indices (BEIs); which refer to the airborne concentrations of chemical substances that workers can be safely exposed to over their working lifetime.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] They are divided into four categories: time-weighted average (TWA), short-term exposure limit (STEL), surface limit (SL), and ceiling (C).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The Threshold Limit Values for Chemical Substances (TLV-CS) Committee was established in 1941.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] This group was charged with investigating, recommending, and annually reviewing exposure limits for chemical substances.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Two years later, the organization adopted its first list of 148 exposure limits, then referred to as Maximum Allowable Concentrations.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The term "Threshold Limit Values (TLV) was introduced in 1956.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The first list of Threshold Limit Values and Biological Exposure Indices (the *TLVs and BEIs* book) was published in 1962*.* A new edition is now published annually.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Today's list of TLVs and BEIs includes over 600 chemical substances and physical agents, as well as over 30 Biological Exposure Indices for selected chemicals.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The TLVs and BEIs are developed as guidelines to assist in the control of health hazards.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] These recommendations or guidelines are intended for use in the practice of industrial hygiene, to be interpreted and applied only by a person trained in this discipline.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] While not enforceable like OSHA's "permissible limit exposures", TLVs and BEIs are still significant and act as advisory numbers to OSHA and to manufacturers who care about workplace safety.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] In certain circumstances, individuals or organizations may wish to make use of these recommendations or guidelines if the use of TLVs and BEIs contributes to the overall improvement in worker protection.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The Foundation for Occupational Health & Safety (FOHS) is an ACGIH supported nonprofit that promotes workplace and worker well-being worldwide through professional education, scientific research in the field and on the profession itself, and the creation of the Sustainable TLV/BEI Fund.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] In 2003, the YIHWAG Family Foundation awarded FOHS a substantial grant to benefit the needs of educational organizations in developing countries throughout the world.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] From this grant, FOHS established the Worldwide Outreach Program.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Its mission is to support the professional development of occupational health and safety throughout the world.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Qualifying educational organizations, professional organizations, and non-government organizations seeking to further the goals of the World Health Organization Collaborating Centers for Occupational Health’s 2006-2010 Work Plan can apply for program grants ranging from $1,000 - $2,000.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] In 2008, FOHS created the Sustainable TLV/BEI Fund.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] The core purpose of the fund is to develop sustainable financial support to ensure the continued existence of ACGIH® TLVs and BEIs.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] Since its inception the core purpose and ‘cause’ of ACGIH has been to protect workplace employees through the development of science-based occupational exposure guidelines widely known as the TLVs and BEIs.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acgih] These guidelines have become recognized throughout the world as forming the scientific basis for subsequent development of workplace standards.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, an **acid dissociation constant** (also known as **acidity constant**, or **acid-ionization constant**; denoted ⁠ $K_{a}$ ⁠) is a quantitative measure of the strength of an acid in solution.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] known as dissociation in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The chemical species HA is an acid that dissociates into A−, called the conjugate base of the acid, and a hydrogen ion, H+.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The system is said to be in equilibrium when the concentrations of its components do not change over time, because both forward and backward reactions are occurring at the same rate.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where quantities in square brackets represent the molar concentrations of the species at equilibrium.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, a hypothetical weak acid having *K*a = 10−5, the value of log *K*a is the exponent (−5), giving p*K*a = 5.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A lower *K*a corresponds to a weaker acid (an acid that is less dissociated at equilibrium).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The form p*K*a is often used because it provides a convenient logarithmic scale, and a lower p*K*a corresponds to a stronger acid.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid dissociation constant for an acid is a direct consequence of the underlying thermodynamics of the dissociation reaction; the p*K*a value is directly proportional to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the reaction.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of the p*K*a changes with temperature and can be understood qualitatively based on Le Chatelier's principle: when the reaction is endothermic, *K*a increases and p*K*a decreases with increasing temperature; the opposite is true for exothermic reactions.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The value of p*K*a also depends on molecular structure of the acid in many ways.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, Linus Pauling proposed two rules: one for successive p*K*a of polyprotic acids (see Polyprotic acids below), and one to estimate the p*K*a of oxyacids based on the number of =O and −OH groups (see Factors that affect p*K*a values below).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other structural factors that influence the magnitude of the acid dissociation constant include inductive effects, mesomeric effects, and hydrogen bonding.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hammett type equations have frequently been applied to the estimation of p*K*a.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantitative behaviour of acids and bases in solution can be understood only if their p*K*a values are known.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In particular, the pH of a solution can be predicted when the analytical concentration and p*K*a values of all acids and bases are known; conversely, it is possible to calculate the equilibrium concentration of the acids and bases in solution when the pH is known.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These calculations find application in many different areas of chemistry, biology, medicine, and geology.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, many compounds used for medication are weak acids or bases, and a knowledge of the p*K*a values, together with the octanol-water partition coefficient, can be used for estimating the extent to which the compound enters the blood stream.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acid dissociation constants are also essential in aquatic chemistry and chemical oceanography, where the acidity of water plays a fundamental role.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In living organisms, acid–base homeostasis and enzyme kinetics are dependent on the p*K*a values of the many acids and bases present in the cell and in the body.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In chemistry, a knowledge of p*K*a values is necessary for the preparation of buffer solutions and is also a prerequisite for a quantitative understanding of the interaction between acids or bases and metal ions to form complexes.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Experimentally, p*K*a values can be determined by potentiometric (pH) titration, but for values of p*K*a less than about 2 or more than about 11, spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be required due to practical difficulties with pH measurements.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constant for this dissociation reaction is known as a dissociation constant.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The acid loses a proton, leaving a conjugate base; the proton is transferred to the base, creating a conjugate acid.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions of an acid HA, the base is water; the conjugate base is A− and the conjugate acid is the hydronium ion.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Brønsted–Lowry definition applies to other solvents, such as dimethyl sulfoxide: the solvent S acts as a base, accepting a proton and forming the conjugate acid SH+.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In solution chemistry, it is common to use H+ as an abbreviation for the solvated hydrogen ion, regardless of the solvent.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated hydronium ion rather than a proton.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The designation of an acid or base as "conjugate" depends on the context.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The hydroxide ion OH−, a well known base, is here acting as the conjugate base of the acid water.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acids and bases are thus regarded simply as donors and acceptors of protons respectively.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A broader definition of acid dissociation includes hydrolysis, in which protons are produced by the splitting of water molecules.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Lewis's original definition, an acid is a substance that accepts an electron pair to form a coordinate covalent bond.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid dissociation constant is a particular example of an equilibrium constant.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $\{X\}$ represents the activity, at equilibrium, of the chemical species X. $K^{\ominus }$ is dimensionless since activity is dimensionless.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Activities of the products of dissociation are placed in the numerator, activities of the reactants are placed in the denominator.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] See activity coefficient for a derivation of this expression.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where $[{\text{HA}}]$ represents the concentration of HA and ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ is a quotient of activity coefficients.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To avoid the complications involved in using activities, dissociation constants are determined, where possible, in a medium of high ionic strength, that is, under conditions in which ⁠ $\Gamma$ ⁠ can be assumed to be always constant.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the medium might be a solution of 0.1 molar (M) sodium nitrate or 3 M potassium perchlorate.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note, however, that all published dissociation constant values refer to the specific ionic medium used in their determination and that different values are obtained with different conditions, as shown for acetic acid in the illustration above.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When published constants refer to an ionic strength other than the one required for a particular application, they may be adjusted by means of specific ion theory (SIT) and other theories.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that in the context of metal-ligand complex formation, the equilibrium constants for the formation of metal complexes are usually defined as *association* constants.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In that case, the equilibrium constants for ligand protonation are also defined as association constants.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When discussing the properties of acids it is usual to specify equilibrium constants as acid dissociation constants, denoted by *K*a, with numerical values given the symbol p*K*a.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the other hand, association constants are used for bases.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, general purpose computer programs that are used to derive equilibrium constant values from experimental data use association constants for both acids and bases.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because stability constants for a metal-ligand complex are always specified as association constants, ligand protonation must also be specified as an association reaction.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The association constant for the formation of a supramolecular complex may be denoted as Ka; in such cases "a" stands for "association", not "acid".
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For polyprotic acids, the numbering of stepwise association constants is the reverse of the numbering of the dissociation constants.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] ⁠ R ⁠ is the gas constant and ⁠ T ⁠ is the absolute temperature.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus, for exothermic reactions, the standard enthalpy change, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠, is negative and *K* decreases with temperature.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For endothermic reactions, ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ is positive and *K* increases with temperature.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where ⁠ $\Delta C_{p}$ ⁠ is the heat capacity change at constant pressure.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice ⁠ $\Delta H^{\ominus }$ ⁠ may be taken to be constant over a small temperature range.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express each concentration value as the ratio c/c0, where c0 is the concentration in a [hypothetical] standard state, with a numerical value of 1, by definition.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Express the concentrations on the mole fraction scale.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since mole fraction has no dimension, the quotient of concentrations will, by definition, be a pure number.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first and second options above give identical numerical values for an equilibrium constant.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is common practice in biochemistry to quote a value with a dimension as, for example, "*K*a = 30 mM" in order to indicate the scale, millimolar (mM) or micromolar (μM) of the concentration values used for its calculation.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid is classified as "strong" when the concentration of its undissociated species is too low to be measured.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Any aqueous acid with a p*K*a value of less than 0 is almost completely deprotonated and is considered a *strong acid*.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] All such acids transfer their protons to water and form the solvent cation species (H3O+ in aqueous solution) so that they all have essentially the same acidity, a phenomenon known as solvent leveling.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They are said to be *fully dissociated* in aqueous solution because the amount of undissociated acid, in equilibrium with the dissociation products, is below the detection limit.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Likewise, any aqueous base with an association constant p*K*b less than about 0, corresponding to p*K*a greater than about 14, is leveled to OH− and is considered a *strong base*.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nitric acid, with a p*K* value of around −1.7, behaves as a strong acid in aqueous solutions with a pH greater than 1.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At lower pH values it behaves as a weak acid.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values for strong acids have been estimated by theoretical means.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the p*K*a value of aqueous HCl has been estimated as −9.3.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the Henderson–Hasselbalch equation, from which the following conclusions can be drawn.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In water, measurable p*K*a values range from about −2 for a strong acid to about 12 for a very weak acid (or strong base).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A buffer solution of a desired pH can be prepared as a mixture of a weak acid and its conjugate base.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In practice, the mixture can be created by dissolving the acid in water, and adding the requisite amount of strong acid or base.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the p*K*a and analytical concentration of the acid are known, the extent of dissociation and pH of a solution of a monoprotic acid can be easily calculated using an ICE table.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A polyprotic acid is a compound which may lose more than 1 proton.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Stepwise dissociation constants are each defined for the loss of a single proton.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The constant for dissociation of the first proton may be denoted as *K*a1 and the constants for dissociation of successive protons as *K*a2, etc.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Phosphoric acid, H3PO4, is an example of a polyprotic acid as it can lose three protons.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The species distribution diagram shows that the concentrations of the two ions are maximum at pH 5.5 and 10.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the difference between successive p*K* values is less than about four there is overlap between the pH range of existence of the species in equilibrium.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The smaller the difference, the more the overlap.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The case of citric acid is shown at the right; solutions of citric acid are buffered over the whole range of pH 2.5 to 7.5.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] According to Pauling's first rule, successive p*K* values of a given acid increase (p*K*a2 > p*K*a1).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For oxyacids with more than one ionizable hydrogen on the same atom, the p*K*a values often increase by about 5 units for each proton removed, as in the example of phosphoric acid above.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It can be seen in the table above that the second proton is removed from a negatively charged species.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Since the proton carries a positive charge extra work is needed to remove it, which is why p*K*a2 is greater than p*K*a1. p*K*a3 is greater than p*K*a2 because there is further charge separation.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When an exception to Pauling's rule is found, it indicates that a major change in structure is also occurring.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case of VO+2(aq), the vanadium is octahedral, 6-coordinate, whereas vanadic acid is tetrahedral, 4-coordinate.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This means that four "particles" are released with the first dissociation, but only two "particles" are released with the other dissociations, resulting in a much greater entropy contribution to the standard Gibbs free energy change for the first reaction than for the others.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For substances in solution, the isoelectric point (p*I*) is defined as the pH at which the sum, weighted by charge value, of concentrations of positively charged species is equal to the weighted sum of concentrations of negatively charged species.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the case that there is one species of each type, the isoelectric point can be obtained directly from the p*K* values.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Take the example of glycine, defined as AH.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] There are two dissociation equilibria to consider.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*I* values for amino acids are listed at proteinogenic amino acid.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When more than two charged species are in equilibrium with each other a full speciation calculation may be needed.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When *K*a, *K*b and *K*w are determined under the same conditions of temperature and ionic strength, it follows, taking cologarithms, that p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] with sufficient accuracy for most practical purposes.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In effect there is no need to define p*K*b separately from p*K*a, but it is done here as often only p*K*b values can be found in the older literature.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is the reciprocal of an association constant for formation of the complex.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Because the relationship p*K*b = p*K*w − p*K*a holds only in aqueous solutions (though analogous relationships apply for other amphoteric solvents), subdisciplines of chemistry like organic chemistry that usually deal with nonaqueous solutions generally do not use p*K*b as a measure of basicity.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Instead, the p*K*a of the conjugate acid, denoted by p*K*aH, is quoted when basicity needs to be quantified.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A higher value for p*K*aH corresponds to a stronger base.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the values p*K*aH (C5H5N) = 5.25 and p*K*aH ((CH3CH2)3N) = 10.75 indicate that (CH3CH2)3N (triethylamine) is a stronger base than C5H5N (pyridine).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amphoteric substance is one that can act as an acid or as a base, depending on pH.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Carbonic acid equilibria are important for acid–base homeostasis in the human body.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An amino acid is also amphoteric with the added complication that the neutral molecule is subject to an internal acid–base equilibrium in which the basic amino group attracts and binds the proton from the acidic carboxyl group, forming a zwitterion.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At pH less than about 5 both the carboxylate group and the amino group are protonated.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At high pH a second dissociation may take place.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Thus the amino acid molecule is amphoteric because it may either be protonated or deprotonated.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The water molecule may either gain or lose a proton.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] where in aqueous solution H+ denotes a solvated proton.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Often this is written as the hydronium ion H3O+, but this formula is not exact because in fact there is solvation by more than one water molecule and species such as H5O+2, H7O+3, and H9O+4 are also present.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The self-ionization constant of water, *K*w, is thus just a special case of an acid dissociation constant.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At that temperature both hydrogen and hydroxide ions have a concentration of 10−7 M.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high donor number, making it a strong Lewis base.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a high dielectric constant (relative permittivity), making it a good solvent for ionic species.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] p*K*a values of organic compounds are often obtained using the aprotic solvents dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO) and acetonitrile (ACN).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] DMSO is widely used as an alternative to water because it has a lower dielectric constant than water, and is less polar and so dissolves non-polar, hydrophobic substances more easily.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It has a measurable p*K*a range of about 1 to 30.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Acetonitrile is less basic than DMSO, and, so, in general, acids are weaker and bases are stronger in this solvent.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Some p*K*a values at 25 °C for acetonitrile (ACN) and dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO). are shown in the following tables.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Values for water are included for comparison.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ionization of acids is less in an acidic solvent than in water.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, hydrogen chloride is a weak acid when dissolved in acetic acid.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This is because acetic acid is a much weaker base than water.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The unlikely geminal diol species CH3C(OH)+2 is stable in these environments.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For aqueous solutions the pH scale is the most convenient acidity function.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other acidity functions have been proposed for non-aqueous media, the most notable being the Hammett acidity function, *H*0, for superacid media and its modified version *H*− for superbasic media.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aprotic solvents, oligomers, such as the well-known acetic acid dimer, may be formed by hydrogen bonding.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] An acid may also form hydrogen bonds to its conjugate base.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This process, known as homoconjugation, has the effect of enhancing the acidity of acids, lowering their effective p*K*a values, by stabilizing the conjugate base.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Homoconjugation enhances the proton-donating power of toluenesulfonic acid in acetonitrile solution by a factor of nearly 800.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aqueous solutions, homoconjugation does not occur, because water forms stronger hydrogen bonds to the conjugate base than does the acid.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a compound has limited solubility in water it is common practice (in the pharmaceutical industry, for example) to determine p*K*a values in a solvent mixture such as water/dioxane or water/methanol, in which the compound is more soluble.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the example shown at the right, the p*K*a value rises steeply with increasing percentage of dioxane as the dielectric constant of the mixture is decreasing.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A p*K*a value obtained in a mixed solvent cannot be used directly for aqueous solutions.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this is that when the solvent is in its standard state its activity is *defined* as one.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the standard state of water:dioxane mixture with 9:1 mixing ratio is precisely that solvent mixture, with no added solutes.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To obtain the p*K*a value for use with aqueous solutions it has to be extrapolated to zero co-solvent concentration from values obtained from various co-solvent mixtures.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These facts are obscured by the omission of the solvent from the expression that is normally used to define p*K*a, but p*K*a values obtained in a *given* mixed solvent can be compared to each other, giving relative acid strengths.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The same is true of p*K*a values obtained in a particular non-aqueous solvent such a DMSO.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A universal, solvent-independent, scale for acid dissociation constants has not been developed, since there is no known way to compare the standard states of two different solvents.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Pauling's second rule is that the value of the first p*K*a for acids of the formula XO*m*(OH)*n* depends primarily on the number of oxo groups *m*, and is approximately independent of the number of hydroxy groups *n*, and also of the central atom X.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alternatively, various numerical formulas have been proposed including p*K*a = 8 − 5*m* (known as Bell's rule), p*K*a = 7 − 5*m*, or p*K*a = 9 − 7*m*.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The dependence on *m* correlates with the oxidation state of the central atom, X: the higher the oxidation state the stronger the oxyacid.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, p*K*a for HClO is 7.2, for HClO2 is 2.0, for HClO3 is −1 and HClO4 is a strong acid (p*K*a ≪ 0).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The increased acidity on adding an oxo group is due to stabilization of the conjugate base by delocalization of its negative charge over an additional oxygen atom.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This rule can help assign molecular structure: for example, phosphorous acid, having molecular formula H3PO3, has a p*K*a near 2, which suggested that the structure is HPO(OH)2, as later confirmed by NMR spectroscopy, and not P(OH)3, which would be expected to have a p*K*a near 8.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Inductive effects and mesomeric effects affect the p*K*a values.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A simple example is provided by the effect of replacing the hydrogen atoms in acetic acid by the more electronegative chlorine atom.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The electron-withdrawing effect of the substituent makes ionisation easier, so successive p*K*a values decrease in the series 4.7, 2.8, 1.4, and 0.7 when 0, 1, 2, or 3 chlorine atoms are present.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The Hammett equation, provides a general expression for the effect of substituents.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Alcohols do not normally behave as acids in water, but the presence of a double bond adjacent to the OH group can substantially decrease the p*K*a by the mechanism of keto–enol tautomerism.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ascorbic acid is an example of this effect.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The diketone 2,4-pentanedione (acetylacetone) is also a weak acid because of the keto–enol equilibrium.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In aromatic compounds, such as phenol, which have an OH substituent, conjugation with the aromatic ring as a whole greatly increases the stability of the deprotonated form.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Structural effects can also be important.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The difference between fumaric acid and maleic acid is a classic example.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid is (E)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid, a *trans* isomer, whereas maleic acid is the corresponding *cis* isomer, i.e.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (Z)-1,4-but-2-enedioic acid (see cis-trans isomerism).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Fumaric acid has p*K*a values of approximately 3.0 and 4.5.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] By contrast, maleic acid has p*K*a values of approximately 1.5 and 6.5.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The reason for this large difference is that when one proton is removed from the *cis* isomer (maleic acid) a strong intramolecular hydrogen bond is formed with the nearby remaining carboxyl group.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This favors the formation of the maleate H+, and it opposes the removal of the second proton from that species.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the *trans* isomer, the two carboxyl groups are always far apart, so hydrogen bonding is not observed.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Proton sponge, 1,8-bis(dimethylamino)naphthalene, has a p*K*a value of 12.1.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is one of the strongest amine bases known.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The high basicity is attributed to the relief of strain upon protonation and strong internal hydrogen bonding.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Effects of the solvent and solvation should be mentioned also in this section.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It turns out, these influences are more subtle than that of a dielectric medium mentioned above.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, the expected (by electronic effects of methyl substituents) and observed in gas phase order of basicity of methylamines, Me3N > Me2NH > MeNH2 > NH3, is changed by water to Me2NH > MeNH2 > Me3N > NH3.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Neutral methylamine molecules are hydrogen-bonded to water molecules mainly through one acceptor, N–HOH, interaction and only occasionally just one more donor bond, NH–OH2.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Hence, methylamines are stabilized to about the same extent by hydration, regardless of the number of methyl groups.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In stark contrast, corresponding methylammonium cations always utilize **all** the available protons for donor NH–OH2 bonding.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Relative stabilization of methylammonium ions thus decreases with the number of methyl groups explaining the order of water basicity of methylamines.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The standard enthalpy change can be determined by calorimetry or by using the van 't Hoff equation, though the calorimetric method is preferable.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When both the standard enthalpy change and acid dissociation constant have been determined, the standard entropy change is easily calculated from the equation above.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In the following table, the entropy terms are calculated from the experimental values of p*K*a and Δ*H*⊖.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The data were critically selected and refer to 25 °C and zero ionic strength, in water.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The first point to note is that, when p*K*a is positive, the standard free energy change for the dissociation reaction is also positive.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Second, some reactions are exothermic and some are endothermic, but, when Δ*H*⊖ is negative *T*ΔS⊖ is the dominant factor, which determines that Δ*G*⊖ is positive.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Last, the entropy contribution is always unfavourable (Δ*S*⊖ < 0) in these reactions.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Ions in aqueous solution tend to orient the surrounding water molecules, which orders the solution and decreases the entropy.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The contribution of an ion to the entropy is the partial molar entropy which is often negative, especially for small or highly charged ions.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The ionization of a neutral acid involves formation of two ions so that the entropy decreases (Δ*S*⊖ < 0).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] On the second ionization of the same acid, there are now three ions and the anion has a charge, so the entropy again decreases.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Note that the *standard* free energy change for the reaction is for the changes *from* the reactants in their standard states *to* the products in their standard states.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The free energy change *at* equilibrium is zero since the chemical potentials of reactants and products are equal at equilibrium.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The experimental determination of p*K*a values is commonly performed by means of titrations, in a medium of high ionic strength and at constant temperature.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A typical procedure would be as follows.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A solution of the compound in the medium is acidified with a strong acid to the point where the compound is fully protonated.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The solution is then titrated with a strong base until all the protons have been removed.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] At each point in the titration pH is measured using a glass electrode and a pH meter.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The equilibrium constants are found by fitting calculated pH values to the observed values, using the method of least squares.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The total volume of added strong base should be small compared to the initial volume of titrand solution in order to keep the ionic strength nearly constant.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This will ensure that p*K*a remains invariant during the titration.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A calculated titration curve for oxalic acid is shown at the right.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Oxalic acid has p*K*a values of 1.27 and 4.27.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Therefore, the buffer regions will be centered at about pH 1.3 and pH 4.3.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The buffer regions carry the information necessary to get the p*K*a values as the concentrations of acid and conjugate base change along a buffer region.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Between the two buffer regions there is an end-point, or equivalence point, at about pH 3.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This end-point is not sharp and is typical of a diprotic acid whose buffer regions overlap by a small amount: p*K*a2 − p*K*a1 is about three in this example.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] (If the difference in p*K* values were about two or less, the end-point would not be noticeable.) The second end-point begins at about pH 6.3 and is sharp.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] This indicates that all the protons have been removed.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When this is so, the solution is not buffered and the pH rises steeply on addition of a small amount of strong base.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] However, the pH does not continue to rise indefinitely.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] A new buffer region begins at about pH 11 (p*K*w − 3), which is where self-ionization of water becomes important.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] It is very difficult to measure pH values of less than two in aqueous solution with a glass electrode, because the Nernst equation breaks down at such low pH values.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] To determine p*K* values of less than about 2 or more than about 11 spectrophotometric or NMR measurements may be used instead of, or combined with, pH measurements.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When the glass electrode cannot be employed, as with non-aqueous solutions, spectrophotometric methods are frequently used.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] These may involve absorbance or fluorescence measurements.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] In both cases the measured quantity is assumed to be proportional to the sum of contributions from each photo-active species; with absorbance measurements the Beer–Lambert law is assumed to apply.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Isothermal titration calorimetry (ITC) may be used to determine both a p*K* value and the corresponding standard enthalpy for acid dissociation.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Software to perform the calculations is supplied by the instrument manufacturers for simple systems.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Aqueous solutions with normal water cannot be used for 1H NMR measurements but heavy water, D2O, must be used instead.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] 13C NMR data, however, can be used with normal water and 1H NMR spectra can be used with non-aqueous media.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The quantities measured with NMR are time-averaged chemical shifts, as proton exchange is fast on the NMR time-scale.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Other chemical shifts, such as those of 31P can be measured.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For some polyprotic acids, dissociation (or association) occurs at more than one nonequivalent site, and the observed macroscopic equilibrium constant, or macro-constant, is a combination of micro-constants involving distinct species.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When one reactant forms two products in parallel, the macro-constant is a sum of two micro-constants, $K=K_{X}+K_{Y}.$ This is true for example for the deprotonation of the amino acid cysteine, which exists in solution as a neutral zwitterion HS−CH2−CH(NH+3)−COO−.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Similarly, a base such as spermine has more than one site where protonation can occur.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] For example, mono-protonation can occur at a terminal −NH2 group or at internal −NH− groups.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] The *K*b values for dissociation of spermine protonated at one or other of the sites are examples of micro-constants.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] They cannot be determined directly by means of pH, absorbance, fluorescence or NMR measurements; a measured *K*b value is the sum of the K values for the micro-reactions.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] Nevertheless, the site of protonation is very important for biological function, so mathematical methods have been developed for the determination of micro-constants.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p01] When a reactant undergoes two reactions in series, the macro-constant for the combined reaction is the product of the micro-constant for the two steps.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the quantitative treatment of systems involving acid–base equilibria in solution.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Many applications exist in biochemistry; for example, the p*K*a values of proteins and amino acid side chains are of major importance for the activity of enzymes and the stability of proteins.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Protein p*K*a values cannot always be measured directly, but may be calculated using theoretical methods.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions are used extensively to provide solutions at or near the physiological pH for the study of biochemical reactions; the design of these solutions depends on a knowledge of the p*K*a values of their components.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Important buffer solutions include MOPS, which provides a solution with pH 7.2, and tricine, which is used in gel electrophoresis.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffering is an essential part of acid base physiology including acid–base homeostasis, and is key to understanding disorders such as acid–base disorder.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The isoelectric point of a given molecule is a function of its p*K* values, so different molecules have different isoelectric points.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This permits a technique called isoelectric focusing, which is used for separation of proteins by 2-D gel polyacrylamide gel electrophoresis.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Buffer solutions also play a key role in analytical chemistry.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] They are used whenever there is a need to fix the pH of a solution at a particular value.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Compared with an aqueous solution, the pH of a buffer solution is relatively insensitive to the addition of a small amount of strong acid or strong base.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The buffer capacity of a simple buffer solution is largest when pH = p*K*a.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In acid–base extraction, the efficiency of extraction of a compound into an organic phase, such as an ether, can be optimised by adjusting the pH of the aqueous phase using an appropriate buffer.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] At the optimum pH, the concentration of the electrically neutral species is maximised; such a species is more soluble in organic solvents having a low dielectric constant than it is in water.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This technique is used for the purification of weak acids and bases.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A pH indicator is a weak acid or weak base that changes colour in the transition pH range, which is approximately p*K*a ± 1.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] The design of a universal indicator requires a mixture of indicators whose adjacent p*K*a values differ by about two, so that their transition pH ranges just overlap.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In pharmacology, ionization of a compound alters its physical behaviour and macro properties such as solubility and lipophilicity, log *p*).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, ionization of any compound will increase the solubility in water, but decrease the lipophilicity.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] This is exploited in drug development to increase the concentration of a compound in the blood by adjusting the p*K*a of an ionizable group.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Knowledge of p*K*a values is important for the understanding of coordination complexes, which are formed by the interaction of a metal ion, Mm+, acting as a Lewis acid, with a ligand, L, acting as a Lewis base.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] To determine the equilibrium constant for this reaction, in which the ligand loses a proton, the p*K*a of the protonated ligand must be known.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In practice, the ligand may be polyprotic; for example EDTA4− can accept four protons; in that case, all p*K*a values must be known.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In addition, the metal ion is subject to hydrolysis, that is, it behaves as a weak acid, so the p*K* values for the hydrolysis reactions must also be known.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Assessing the hazard associated with an acid or base may require a knowledge of p*K*a values.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] For example, hydrogen cyanide is a very toxic gas, because the cyanide ion inhibits the iron-containing enzyme cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Hydrogen cyanide is a weak acid in aqueous solution with a p*K*a of about 9.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In strongly alkaline solutions, above pH 11, say, it follows that sodium cyanide is "fully dissociated" so the hazard due to the hydrogen cyanide gas is much reduced.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] An acidic solution, on the other hand, is very hazardous because all the cyanide is in its acid form.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Ingestion of cyanide by mouth is potentially fatal, independently of pH, because of the reaction with cytochrome c oxidase.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] In environmental science acid–base equilibria are important for lakes and rivers; for example, humic acids are important components of natural waters.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] There are multiple techniques to determine the p*K*a of a chemical, leading to some discrepancies between different sources.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Well measured values are typically within 0.1 units of each other.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] Data presented here were taken at 25 °C in water.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] More values can be found in the Thermodynamics section, above.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acid-dissociation-constant-p02] A table of p*K*a of carbon acids, measured in DMSO, can be found on the page on carbanions.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] An **acrylic resin** is a thermoplastic or thermosetting plastic substance typically derived from acrylic acid, methacrylic acid and acrylate monomers such as butyl acrylate and methacrylate monomers such as methyl methacrylate.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] Thermoplastic acrylics designate a group of acrylic resins typically containing both a high molecular weight and a high glass transition temperature which exhibit lacquer dry capability.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] Acrylic resins designed for use in two component systems for crosslinking with isocyanate are referred to as polyols and are made with the monomers previously mentioned as well as hydroxy monomers such as hydroxy ethyl methacrylate.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] Acrylic resins are produced in different liquid carriers such as a hydrocarbon solvent (solventborne acrylics or solution acrylics solventborne acrylic selector) or water in which case they are referred to as emulsions or dispersions and they are also provided in 100% solids bead form.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] One example is polyhydroxyethylmethacrylate (pHEMA), which makes a crosslinked polymer when treated with polyisocyanates.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] Such materials are a useful component in some paints.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] Acrylic resin is a common ingredient in latex paint (UK: "emulsion paint").
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] Latex paints with a greater proportion of acrylic resin offer better stain protection, greater water resistance, better adhesion, greater resistance to cracking and blistering, and resistance to alkali cleaners compared to those with vinyl.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] Acrylic resin is considered extremely weatherproof and is well-suited for outdoor applications.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] In solid form, acrylic resin can last for decades.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] It does not yellow when exposed to sunlight, even after many years.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] Acrylic resins are the materials which when added to latex increases its gloss properties, mechanical durability (i.e. scratch resistance) and improves the gloss over vinyl-only resins.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/acrylic-resin] Melanin-producing *Cladosporium* fungi damaged dried acrylic resin samples in the Milan Cathedral.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Genetic evidence from comparisons of multiple organisms showed that a glutathione-dependent formaldehyde dehydrogenase, identical to a class III alcohol dehydrogenase (ADH-3/ADH5), is presumed to be the ancestral enzyme for the entire ADH family.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Early on in evolution, an effective method for eliminating both endogenous and exogenous formaldehyde was important and this capacity has conserved the ancestral ADH-3 through time.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Gene duplication of ADH-3, followed by series of mutations, led to the evolution of other ADHs.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The ability to produce ethanol from sugar (which is the basis of how alcoholic beverages are made) is believed to have initially evolved in yeast.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Though this feature is not adaptive from an energy point of view, by making alcohol in such high concentrations so that they would be toxic to other organisms, yeast cells could effectively eliminate their competition.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Since rotting fruit can contain more than 4% of ethanol, animals eating the fruit needed a system to metabolize exogenous ethanol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] This was thought to explain the conservation of ethanol active ADH in species other than yeast, though ADH-3 is now known to also have a major role in nitric oxide signaling.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In humans, sequencing of the ADH1B gene (responsible for production of an alcohol dehydrogenase polypeptide) shows several functional variants.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In one, there is a SNP (single nucleotide polymorphism) that leads to either a Histidine or an Arginine residue at position 47 in the mature polypeptide.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In the Histidine variant, the enzyme is much more effective at the aforementioned conversion.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The enzyme responsible for the conversion of acetaldehyde to acetate, however, remains unaffected, which leads to differential rates of substrate catalysis and causes a buildup of toxic acetaldehyde, causing cell damage.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] This provides some protection against excessive alcohol consumption and alcohol dependence (alcoholism).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Various haplotypes arising from this mutation are more concentrated in regions near Eastern China, a region also known for its low alcohol tolerance and dependence.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] A study was conducted in order to find a correlation between allelic distribution and alcoholism, and the results suggest that the allelic distribution arose along with rice cultivation in the region between 12,000 and 6,000 years ago.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In regions where rice was cultivated, rice was also fermented into ethanol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] This led to speculation that increased alcohol availability led to alcoholism and abuse, resulting in lower reproductive fitness.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Those with the variant allele have little tolerance for alcohol, thus lowering chance of dependence and abuse.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The hypothesis posits that those individuals with the Histidine variant enzyme were sensitive enough to the effects of alcohol that differential reproductive success arose and the corresponding alleles were passed through the generations.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Classical Darwinian evolution would act to select against the detrimental form of the enzyme (Arg variant) because of the lowered reproductive success of individuals carrying the allele.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The result would be a higher frequency of the allele responsible for the His-variant enzyme in regions that had been under selective pressure the longest.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The distribution and frequency of the His variant follows the spread of rice cultivation to inland regions of Asia, with higher frequencies of the His variant in regions that have cultivated rice the longest.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The geographic distribution of the alleles seems to therefore be a result of natural selection against individuals with lower reproductive success, namely, those who carried the Arg variant allele and were more susceptible to alcoholism.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] However, the persistence of the Arg variant in other populations argues that the effect could not be strong.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The enzyme was first found by Detlev Müller in 1933.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The first-ever isolated alcohol dehydrogenase (ADH) was purified in 1937 from *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* (brewer's yeast).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Many aspects of the catalytic mechanism for the horse liver ADH enzyme were investigated by Hugo Theorell and coworkers.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] ADH was also one of the first oligomeric enzymes that had its amino acid sequence and three-dimensional structure determined.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In early 1960, the alcohol dehydrogenase (*ADH*) gene was discovered in fruit flies of the genus *Drosophila melanogaster.* Flies that are mutant for ADH cannot breakdown alcohols into aldehydes and ketones.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] While ethanol produced by decaying fruit is a natural food source and location for oviposit for *Drosophila* at low concentrations (<4%), high concentrations of ethanol can induce oxidative stress and alcohol intoxication.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] *Drosophila's* fitness is elevated by consuming the low concentration of ethanol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Initial exposure to ethanol causes hyperactivity, followed by incoordination and sedation.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Further research has shown that the antioxidant alpha-ketoglutarate may be beneficial in reducing the oxidative stress produced by alcohol consumption.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] A 2016 study concluded that food supplementation with 10-mM alpha-ketoglutarate decreased *Drosophila* alcohol sensitivity over time.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] For the gene that codes for ADH, there are 194 known classic and insertion alleles.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Two alleles that are commonly used for experimentation involving ethanol toxicity and response are ADHs (slow) and ADHF (fast).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Numerous experiments have concluded that the two alleles account for the differences in enzymatic activity for each.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Haplosuffiency means that having one functioning allele will be adequate in producing the needed phenotypes for survival.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] That means that flies that were heterozygous for the Adh allele (one copy of the Adh null allele and one copy of the Adh Wild type allele) gave very similar phenotypical alcohol tolerance as the homozygous dominant flies (two copies of the wild type Adh allele).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Regardless of genotype, *Drosophila* show a negative response to exposure to samples with an ethanol content above 5%, which render any tolerance inadequate, resulting in a lethal dosage and a mortality rate of around 70%.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] *Drosophila* show many of the same ethanol responses as humans do.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Low doses of ethanol produce hyperactivity, moderate doses incoordination, and high doses sedation.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The alcohol dehydrogenases comprise a group of several isozymes that catalyse the oxidation of primary and secondary alcohols to aldehydes and ketones, respectively, and also can catalyse the reverse reaction.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In mammals this is a redox (reduction/oxidation) reaction involving the coenzyme nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD+).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The mechanism in yeast and bacteria is the reverse of this reaction.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] These steps are supported through kinetic studies.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The substrate is coordinated to the zinc and this enzyme has two zinc atoms per subunit.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] One is the active site, which is involved in catalysis.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In the active site, the ligands are Cys-46, Cys-174, His-67, and one water molecule.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The other subunit is involved with structure.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In this mechanism, the hydride from the alcohol goes to NAD+.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Crystal structures indicate that the His-51 deprotonates the nicotinamide ribose, which deprotonates Ser-48.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Finally, Ser-48 deprotonates the alcohol, making it an aldehyde.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] From a mechanistic perspective, if the enzyme adds hydride to the re face of NAD+, the resulting hydrogen is incorporated into the pro-R position.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Enzymes that add hydride to the re face are deemed Class A dehydrogenases.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In the commonly studied horse liver isoform, Thr-48 is a Ser, and Leu-319 is a Phe.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The zinc coordinates the substrate (alcohol).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The zinc is coordinated by Cys-46, Cys-174, and His-67.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Leu-319, Ala-317, His-51, Ile-269 and Val-292 stabilize NAD+ by forming hydrogen bonds.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] His-51 and Ile-269 form hydrogen bonds with the alcohols on nicotinamide ribose.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Phe-319, Ala-317 and Val-292 form hydrogen bonds with the amide on NAD+.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Mammalian alcohol dehydrogenases also have a structural zinc site.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] This Zn ion plays a structural role and is crucial for protein stability.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The structures of the catalytic and structural zinc sites in horse liver alcohol dehydrogenase (HLADH) as revealed in crystallographic structures, which has been studied computationally with quantum chemistry as well as with classical molecular dynamics methods.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The structural zinc site is composed of four closely spaced cysteine ligands (Cys97, Cys100, Cys103, and Cys111 in the amino acid sequence) positioned in an almost symmetric tetrahedron around the Zn ion.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] A recent study showed that the interaction between zinc and cysteine is governed by primarily an electrostatic contribution with an additional covalent contribution to the binding.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In humans, ADH exists in multiple forms as a dimer and is encoded by at least seven genes.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Among the five classes (I-V) of alcohol dehydrogenase, the hepatic forms that are used primarily in humans are class 1.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Class 1 consists of α, β, and γ subunits that are encoded by the genes ADH1A, ADH1B, and ADH1C.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The enzyme is present at high levels in the liver and the lining of the stomach.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] This allows the consumption of alcoholic beverages, but its evolutionary purpose is probably the breakdown of alcohols naturally contained in foods or produced by bacteria in the digestive tract.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Another evolutionary purpose is reversible metabolism of retinol (vitamin A), an alcohol, to retinaldehyde, also known as retinal, which is then irreversibly converted into retinoic acid, which regulates expression of hundreds of genes.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Alcohol dehydrogenase is also involved in the toxicity of other types of alcohol: For instance, it oxidizes methanol to produce formaldehyde and ultimately formic acid.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Humans have at least six slightly different alcohol dehydrogenases.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Each is a dimer (i.e., consists of two polypeptides), with each dimer containing two zinc ions Zn2+.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] One of those ions is crucial for the operation of the enzyme: It is located at the catalytic site and holds the hydroxyl group of the alcohol in place.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Alcohol dehydrogenase activity varies between men and women, between young and old, and among populations from different areas of the world.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] For example, young women are unable to process alcohol at the same rate as young men because they do not express the alcohol dehydrogenase as highly, although the inverse is true among the middle-aged.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The level of activity may not be dependent only on level of expression but also on allelic diversity among the population.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The human genes that encode class II, III, IV, and V alcohol dehydrogenases are ADH4, ADH5, ADH7, and ADH6, respectively.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Unlike humans, yeast and bacteria (except lactic acid bacteria, and *E. coli* in certain conditions) do not ferment glucose to lactate.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Instead, they ferment it to ethanol and CO2.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In yeast and many bacteria, alcohol dehydrogenase plays an important part in fermentation: Pyruvate resulting from glycolysis is converted to acetaldehyde and carbon dioxide, and the acetaldehyde is then reduced to ethanol by an alcohol dehydrogenase called ADH1.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The purpose of this latter step is the regeneration of NAD+, so that the energy-generating glycolysis can continue.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Humans exploit this process to produce alcoholic beverages, by letting yeast ferment various fruits or grains.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Yeast can produce and consume their own alcohol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The main alcohol dehydrogenase in yeast is larger than the human one, consisting of four rather than just two subunits.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] It also contains zinc at its catalytic site.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Together with the zinc-containing alcohol dehydrogenases of animals and humans, these enzymes from yeasts and many bacteria form the family of "long-chain"-alcohol dehydrogenases.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Brewer's yeast also has another alcohol dehydrogenase, ADH2, which evolved out of a duplicate version of the chromosome containing the ADH1 gene.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] ADH2 is used by the yeast to convert ethanol back into acetaldehyde, and it is expressed only when sugar concentration is low.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Having these two enzymes allows yeast to produce alcohol when sugar is plentiful (and this alcohol then kills off competing microbes), and then continue with the oxidation of the alcohol once the sugar, and competition, is gone.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In plants, ADH catalyses the same reaction as in yeast and bacteria to ensure that there is a constant supply of NAD+.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Maize has two versions of ADH – ADH1 and ADH2, *Arabidopsis thaliana* contains only one ADH gene.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The structure of *Arabidopsis* ADH is 47%-conserved, relative to ADH from horse liver.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Structurally and functionally important residues, such as the seven residues that provide ligands for the catalytic and noncatalytic zinc atoms, however, are conserved, suggesting that the enzymes have a similar structure.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] ADH is constitutively expressed at low levels in the roots of young plants grown on agar.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] If the roots lack oxygen, the expression of *ADH* increases significantly.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Its expression is also increased in response to dehydration, to low temperatures, and to abscisic acid, and it plays an important role in fruit ripening, seedlings development, and pollen development.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Differences in the sequences of *ADH* in different species have been used to create phylogenies showing how closely related different species of plants are.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] It is an ideal gene to use due to its convenient size (2–3 kb in length with a ≈1000 nucleotide coding sequence) and low copy number.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] A third family of alcohol dehydrogenases, unrelated to the above two, are iron-containing ones.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In comparison to enzymes of the above families, these enzymes are oxygen-sensitive.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] A further class of alcohol dehydrogenases belongs to quinoenzymes and requires quinoid cofactors (e.g., pyrroloquinoline quinone, PQQ) as enzyme-bound electron acceptors.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] A typical example for this type of enzyme is methanol dehydrogenase of methylotrophic bacteria.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Alcohol dehydrogenases are often used for the synthesis of enantiomerically pure stereoisomers of chiral alcohols.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Often, high chemo- and enantioselectivity can be achieved.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] One example is the alcohol dehydrogenase from *Lactobacillus brevis* (*Lb*ADH), which is described to be a versatile biocatalyst.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The high chemospecificity has been confirmed also in the case of substrates presenting two potential redox sites.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] For instance cinnamaldehyde presents both aliphatic double bond and aldehyde function.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Unlike conventional catalysts, alcohol dehydrogenases are able to selectively act only on the latter, yielding exclusively cinnamyl alcohol.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] In fuel cells, alcohol dehydrogenases can be used to catalyze the breakdown of fuel for an ethanol fuel cell.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Scientists at Saint Louis University have used carbon-supported alcohol dehydrogenase with poly(methylene green) as an anode, with a nafion membrane, to achieve about 50 μA/cm2.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Racker defined one unit of alcohol dehydrogenase activity as the amount that causes a change in optical density of 0.001 per minute under the standard conditions of assay.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Recently, the international definition of enzymatic unit (E.U.) has been more common: one unit of Alcohol Dehydrogenase will convert 1.0 μmole of ethanol to acetaldehyde per minute at pH 8.8 at 25 °C.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] There have been studies showing that variations in ADH that influence ethanol metabolism have an impact on the risk of alcohol dependence.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The strongest effect is due to variations in ADH1B that increase the rate at which alcohol is converted to acetaldehyde.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] One such variant is most common in individuals from East Asia and the Middle East, another is most common in individuals from Africa.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Both variants reduce the risk for alcoholism, but individuals can become alcoholic despite that.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Researchers have tentatively detected a few other genes to be associated with alcoholism, and know that there must be many more remaining to be found.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Research continues in order to identify the genes and their influence on alcoholism.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Drug dependence is another problem associated with ADH, which researchers think might be linked to alcoholism.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] One particular study suggests that drug dependence has seven ADH genes associated with it, however, more research is necessary.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Alcohol dependence and other drug dependence may share some risk factors, but because alcohol dependence is often comorbid with other drug dependences, the association of ADH with the other drug dependencies may not be causal.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Fomepizole, a drug that competitively inhibits alcohol dehydrogenase, can be used in the setting of acute methanol or ethylene glycol toxicity.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] This prevents the conversion of the methanol or ethylene glycol to its toxic metabolites (such as formic acid, formaldehyde, or glycolate).
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The same effect is also sometimes achieved with ethanol, again by competitive inhibition of ADH.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] The drug hydroxyzine is broken down into its main metabolite cetirizine by alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:2-butoxyethanol/alcohol-dehydrogenase] Other drugs with alcohol groups may be metabolized in a similar way as long as steric hindrance does not prevent the alcohol from reaching the active site.
